Diversity may provide several advantages, such as offering a variety of viewpoints and ideas to a group or organization, promoting creativity and innovation, and assisting in the creation of an inclusive culture. It may, however, provide obstacles, such as communication difficulties and possible confrontations between diverse groups. Diversity is more likely to be advantageous in circumstances requiring a broad range of viewpoints and ideas, such as problem solving or decision-making. It may also help when a varied group or organization is better suited to serve a diverse community. Diversity, on the other hand, may be least useful when a homogenous group is required for a certain job or when a single opinion is more vital than a variety of views. It may also be less useful in instances when people lack cultural competence or are unwilling to learn from or work with persons from various backgrounds. 